Introduction to Analysis-1¶

Analysis of percentage of sales for each household¶

By categorizing households according to their total sales in a year, it becomes possible to analyze the percentage of sales generated by each category of people. This provides a more nuanced understanding of consumer behavior and enables businesses to tailor their marketing strategies to specific segments of the population, ultimately leading to more effective targeting and increased revenue.

In [265]:
household_summary = (transactions.groupby('household_id')
.agg({'sales_value': 'sum'})
.reset_index()
.rename(columns={'sales_value': 'overall_sales'})
.sort_values(by='overall_sales', ascending=False)
)

household_summary['check_value'] = 1
household_summary['cum_check_value'] = household_summary['check_value'].cumsum()
household_summary['perc_check_value'] = (household_summary['cum_check_value']*100/
household_summary['check_value'].sum())
conditions = [
household_summary['perc_check_value'] <= 25,
(household_summary['perc_check_value'] > 25) & (household_summary['perc_check_value'] <= 50),
(household_summary['perc_check_value'] > 50) & (household_summary['perc_check_value'] <= 75),
household_summary['perc_check_value'] > 75,
]
choices = ['Top 25 %', 'Btw 25-50 %', 'Btw 50-75 %', 'Last 25 %']
household_summary['quantile_groups'] = np.select(conditions, choices)

household_summary = (household_summary.groupby('quantile_groups')
.agg({'overall_sales': 'sum'})
.reset_index()
.sort_values(by='overall_sales', ascending=False)
)

household_summary['overall_sales_perc'] = (household_summary['overall_sales']*100/
household_summary['overall_sales'].sum())

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
sns.barplot(x='quantile_groups', y='overall_sales_perc', data=household_summary,
palette='viridis')
plt.title('% Contribution of sales by each consumer group')
plt.xlabel('Consumer groups')
plt.ylabel('% sales contribution')
plt.show()

So, we can say that these top 25% of consumers are important from the investment and marketing point of view¶

We can clearly see the contribution of top 25% consumers is highest with around 60% Out of 2,469 households around 420 consumers are classified as top consumers

# Inner join coupons, campaign_descriptions, and transactions tables
fa = pd.merge(coupons, campaign_descriptions, on='campaign_id', how='inner')
fa = pd.merge(fa, transactions, on='product_id', how='inner')

# Convert transaction_timestamp to date
fa['transaction_timestamp'] = pd.to_datetime(fa['transaction_timestamp'])

# Create match column
fa['match'] = (fa['transaction_timestamp'].between(fa['start_date'], fa['end_date'])).astype(int)

# Calculate total quantity sold without campaign and with campaign
l1 = fa.loc[fa['match'] == 0].groupby('product_id').agg(total_qunatity_sold_no_camp=('quantity', 'sum'))
l2 = fa.loc[fa['match'] == 1].groupby('product_id').agg(total_quantity_sold_camp=('quantity', 'sum'))

# Join the two tables and calculate Opportunity factor
joined = l1.join(l2).reset_index()
joined['Opportunity_factor'] = round((joined['total_quantity_sold_camp'] - joined['total_qunatity_sold_no_camp']) / joined['total_qunatity_sold_no_camp'], 2)

# Select top 10 products with highest Opportunity factor
top_10 = joined.nlargest(10, 'Opportunity_factor')

Introduction to Analysis-3¶

For this analysis, we are focusing on identifying demographics with a high sensitivity to campaigns or promotions for any discounted products. To accomplish this, we analysed the total sales for Regork as two parts: a)The first being total sales with respect to all of the different factors in demographics. b)The second was sales for only discounted items (all discounts like retail, coupon, coupon_match were considered for this analysis) While looking at these trends with respect to all the different factors, we noted some interesting insights, and only those were presented here to keep it concise. The general idea is that if the trend with demographics is different from total sales to discounted items sales,we can identify certain demographics whose sales are being affected because of the discounts placed on items.

Data Preparation¶

Since each demographics has representation that varies in number, calculating the total sales to compare each demographics would not work in this case. So average sales for each demographic was looked at in our Analysis. we’ve calculated factors for each demographics, which will be used to calculate the respective Average sales. Since our focus was on Demographics, we will only be looking at transactions for which we have the demographics data.

In [284]:
# demographics_income
demographics_income = demographics.groupby('income').size().reset_index(name='n')
demographics_income['income_factor'] = 1 / demographics_income['n']

# demographics_age
demographics_age = demographics.groupby('age').size().reset_index(name='n')
demographics_age['age_factor'] = 1 / demographics_age['n']

# demographics_kidscount
demographics_kidscount = demographics.groupby('kids_count').size().reset_index(name='n')
demographics_kidscount['kids_count_factor'] = 1 / demographics_kidscount['n']

# demographics_householdsize
demographics_householdsize = demographics.groupby('household_size').size().reset_index(name='n')
demographics_householdsize['household_size_factor'] = 1 / demographics_householdsize['n']

# demographics_maritalstatus
demographics_maritalstatus = demographics.groupby('marital_status').size().reset_index(name='n')
demographics_maritalstatus['marital_status_factor'] = 1 / demographics_maritalstatus['n']

# households_per_campaign
households_per_campaign = campaigns.groupby('campaign_id').size().reset_index(name='n')
households_per_campaign['households_per_campaign_factor'] = 1 / households_per_campaign['n']

In [285]:
filtered_transactions = transactions.loc[
    (transactions['retail_disc'] > 0) |
    (transactions['coupon_disc'] > 0) |
    (transactions['coupon_match_disc'] > 0)
]
merged = pd.merge(filtered_transactions, demographics, on='household_id')
sales_by_income = merged.groupby('income').agg(totalsales=('sales_value', 'sum'))

merged_income = pd.merge(sales_by_income, demographics_income, on='income')
merged_income['avgsales'] = merged_income['totalsales'] * merged_income['income_factor']
result = merged_income[['income', 'totalsales', 'avgsales']].sort_values(by='avgsales', ascending=False)

# Plotting
def format(x, _):
    return f'${x:,.0f}'

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
ax = result.plot(kind='bar', x='income', y='avgsales', color='orange', legend=False)
ax.set_title('Discounted item sales by demographics income')
ax.set_ylabel('Average sales in $')
ax.set_xlabel('Income Range of Households')
ax.xaxis.set_tick_params(rotation=90)
ax.yaxis.set_major_formatter(FuncFormatter(format))
plt.show()

joined = pd.merge(filtered, demographics, on='household_id', how='inner')

# group by household_size and calculate the sum of sales_value
grouped = joined.groupby('household_size').agg(totalsales=('sales_value', 'sum'))

# join with demographics_householdsize on household_size

Limitations:¶

  1. Demographics data is not available for all the households
  2. There are some transactions with incomplete transaction information.
  3. Order of sales for product categories between the top 25% consumers and overall consumers there is not much difference
